# nl-rag distilled facts ÔÇö domain: complex-analysis
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:complex-analysis/analytic-function] In mathematical analysis, an **analytic function** is a function that is locally represented by a convergent power series.
[src:complex-analysis/analytic-function] More precisely, a real or complex function is analytic at a point if, in some neighborhood of that point, it is equal to a power series centered there.
[src:complex-analysis/analytic-function] Analytic functions are therefore locally determined by their coefficients, or equivalently by their derivatives at the center of the expansion.
[src:complex-analysis/analytic-function] In other words, an analytic function is a function that is locally represented by a convergent Taylor series.
[src:complex-analysis/analytic-function] Analytic functions occur in both real analysis and complex analysis, in slightly different ways.
[src:complex-analysis/analytic-function] A real or complex analytic function is necessarily smooth, having derivatives of all orders.
[src:complex-analysis/analytic-function] But a smooth real function need not be analytic.
[src:complex-analysis/analytic-function] By contrast, a complex function on an open set is analytic if and only if it is holomorphic, that is, complex differentiable at every point of the set.
[src:complex-analysis/analytic-function] For this reason, in complex analysis the terms *analytic function* and *holomorphic function* are often used interchangeably.
[src:complex-analysis/analytic-function] The terms **complex analytic** and **real analytic** distinguish between these cases.
[src:complex-analysis/analytic-function] In signal processing, a complex analytic function is sometimes called an analytic signal.
[src:complex-analysis/analytic-function] Analyticity is a strong regularity condition.
[src:complex-analysis/analytic-function] Analytic functions have rigid local behavior: for example, on a connected domain, an analytic function whose zeros have an accumulation point must vanish identically.
[src:complex-analysis/analytic-function] Standard examples include polynomials, the exponential function, and the trigonometric functions on their domains of analyticity.
[src:complex-analysis/analytic-function] Alternatively, a real analytic function is an infinitely differentiable function such that the Taylor series at each point $x_{0}$ in its domain $T(x)=\sum _{n=0}^{\infty }{\frac {f^{(n)}(x_{0})}{n!}}(x-x_{0})^{n}$ converges to $f(x)$ for x in a neighborhood of $x_{0}$ pointwise.
[src:complex-analysis/analytic-function] The set of all real analytic functions on a given set D is often denoted by Ôüá ${\mathcal {C}}^{\omega }(D)$ Ôüá, or just by ${\mathcal {C}}^{\omega }$ if the domain is understood.
[src:complex-analysis/analytic-function] A function f defined on some subset of the real line is said to be real analytic at a point x if there is a neighborhood D of x on which f is real analytic.
[src:complex-analysis/analytic-function] The definition of a *complex analytic function* is obtained by replacing, in the definitions above, "real" with "complex" and "real line" with "complex plane".
[src:complex-analysis/analytic-function] A function is complex analytic if and only if it is holomorphic i.e. it is complex differentiable.
[src:complex-analysis/analytic-function] For this reason the terms "holomorphic" and "analytic" are often used interchangeably for such functions.
[src:complex-analysis/analytic-function] In complex analysis, a function is called analytic in an open set Ôüá U Ôüá if it is (complex) differentiable at each point in Ôüá U Ôüá.
[src:complex-analysis/analytic-function] There is a complex analytic extension of f to an open set $G\subset \mathbb {C}$ that contains Ôüá D Ôüá.
[src:complex-analysis/analytic-function] Complex analytic functions are exactly equivalent to holomorphic functions, and are thus much more easily characterized.
[src:complex-analysis/analytic-function] For the case of an analytic function with several variables (see below), the real analyticity can be characterized using the FourierÔÇôBrosÔÇôIagolnitzer transform.
[src:complex-analysis/analytic-function] In the multivariable case, real analytic functions satisfy a direct generalization of the third characterization.
[src:complex-analysis/analytic-function] Let $U\subset \mathbb {R} ^{n}$ be an open set, and let Ôüá $f:U\to \mathbb {R}$ Ôüá.
[src:complex-analysis/analytic-function] A polynomial cannot be zero at too many points unless it is the zero polynomial (more precisely, the number of zeros is at most the degree of the polynomial).
[src:complex-analysis/analytic-function] A similar but weaker statement holds for analytic functions.
[src:complex-analysis/analytic-function] If the set of zeros of an analytic function Ôüá f Ôüá has an accumulation point inside its domain, then Ôüá f Ôüá is zero everywhere on the connected component containing the accumulation point.
[src:complex-analysis/analytic-function] In other words, if Ôüá $(r_{n})$ Ôüá is a sequence of distinct numbers such that Ôüá $f(r_{n})=0$ Ôüá for all Ôüá n Ôüá and this sequence converges to a point Ôüá r Ôüá in the domain of Ôüá D Ôüá, then Ôüá f Ôüá is identically zero on the connected component of Ôüá D Ôüá containing Ôüá r Ôüá.
[src:complex-analysis/analytic-function] Also, if all the derivatives of an analytic function at a point are zero, the function is constant on the corresponding connected component.
[src:complex-analysis/analytic-function] These statements imply that while analytic functions do have more degrees of freedom than polynomials, they are still quite rigid.
[src:complex-analysis/analytic-function] As noted above, any function (real or complex) is infinitely differentiable on a neighborhood where it is equal to a convergent power series.
[src:complex-analysis/analytic-function] In a neighborhood of a point of analyticity, there is a convergent power series equal to the function in the neighborhood, so the function is infinitely differentiable there.
[src:complex-analysis/analytic-function] There exist smooth real functions that are not analytic: see *Non-analytic smooth function*.
[src:complex-analysis/analytic-function] The situation is quite different when one considers complex analytic functions and complex derivatives.
[src:complex-analysis/analytic-function] Any complex-differentiable function in an open disc centered at $z=z_{0}$ (holomorphic function) is analytic there, and conversely any function given by a convergent power series in the complex variable $z-z_{0}$ is complex differentiable (and infinitely differentiable) on the disk of convergence.
[src:complex-analysis/analytic-function] Consequently, in complex analysis, the term *analytic function* is synonymous with *holomorphic function*.
[src:complex-analysis/analytic-function] Real and complex analytic functions have important differences (one could notice that even from their different relationship with differentiability).
[src:complex-analysis/analytic-function] Analyticity of complex functions is a more restrictive property, as it has more restrictive necessary conditions and complex analytic functions have more structure than their real-line counterparts.
[src:complex-analysis/analytic-function] According to Liouville's theorem, any bounded complex analytic function defined on the whole complex plane is constant.
[src:complex-analysis/analytic-function] Also, if a complex analytic function is defined in an open ball around a point Ôüá $x_{0}$ Ôüá, its power series expansion at Ôüá $x_{0}$ Ôüá is convergent in the whole open ball (holomorphic functions are analytic).
[src:complex-analysis/analytic-function] Any real analytic function on some open set on the real line can be extended to a complex analytic function on some open set of the complex plane.
[src:complex-analysis/analytic-function] However, not every real analytic function defined on the whole real line can be extended to a complex function defined on the whole complex plane.
[src:complex-analysis/analytic-function] The function Ôüá $f(x)$ Ôüá defined in the paragraph above is a counterexample, as it is not defined for Ôüá $x=\pm i$ Ôüá.
[src:complex-analysis/analytic-function] If a function is analytic at a , then its Taylor series converges *to the function* in some open neighborhood of a .
[src:complex-analysis/analytic-function] More generally, for any power series $\sum _{n=0}^{\infty }c_{n}(x-a)^{n},$ there is a number R called the radius of convergence, which can be any non-negative number or $+\infty$ , such that the power series converges absolutely for $|x-a|<R$ and diverges for $|x-a|>R$ .
[src:complex-analysis/analytic-function] Thus, when a Taylor series converges, it does so in an open interval centered at a in the real case, or a disc centered at a in the complex case.
[src:complex-analysis/analytic-function] A Taylor series may converge absolutely or conditionally at some, all, or none of the boundary points of the open interval or disc.
[src:complex-analysis/analytic-function] In complex analysis, the radius of convergence of a holomorphic function at a point is the radius of the largest open disc centered at that point on which the function remains holomorphic.
[src:complex-analysis/analytic-function] In many common cases, this is the distance to the nearest singularity of the function in the complex plane.
[src:complex-analysis/analytic-function] This explains the different radii of convergence for familiar Taylor series.
[src:complex-analysis/analytic-function] The series for $e^{z}$ , $\sin z$ , and $\cos z$ have infinite radius of convergence because these are entire functions, having no singularities in the complex plane.
[src:complex-analysis/analytic-function] By contrast, the Taylor series for $\log(1+z)$ around $z=0$ has radius of convergence 1 , because the nearest singularity is at $z=-1$ .
[src:complex-analysis/analytic-function] Complex singularities can determine the radius of convergence even for functions that are smooth on the real line.
[src:complex-analysis/analytic-function] For example, although $f(x)={\frac {1}{1+x^{2}}}$ is smooth for all real x , the radius of convergence of its Taylor series around $x=0$ is 1 , because the corresponding complex function has singularities at $x=i$ and $x=-i$ , which are points of the complex unit circle.
[src:complex-analysis/analytic-function] A power series may converge at every point of the boundary of its disc of convergence and still fail to extend holomorphically beyond that disc.
[src:complex-analysis/analytic-function] For example, if $\alpha >0$ is not an integer, then the binomial series $(1+z)^{\alpha }=\sum _{n=0}^{\infty }{\binom {\alpha }{n}}z^{n}$ has radius of convergence $R=1$ .
[src:complex-analysis/analytic-function] The series converges everywhere on the closed unit disc, including every boundary point.
[src:complex-analysis/analytic-function] However, for nonintegral $\alpha$ , the function $(1+z)^{\alpha }$ does not extend as a single-valued holomorphic function to any neighborhood of $z=-1$ .
[src:complex-analysis/analytic-function] Thus the obstruction to analytic continuation at the boundary point $z=-1$ is not a failure of convergence of the power series, nor a pole or essential singularity, but the branching of the analytic continuation.
[src:complex-analysis/analytic-function] In effect, $z=-1$ is a branch point of the function.
[src:complex-analysis/analytic-function] This illustrates that convergence on the closed disc is weaker than holomorphic extendibility beyond the boundary.
[src:complex-analysis/analytic-function] Because analytic functions are locally represented by power series, a value of the function on one small neighborhood can sometimes determine values on a larger region.
[src:complex-analysis/analytic-function] This process is called analytic continuation.
[src:complex-analysis/analytic-function] Starting with a power series representation in one neighborhood, one can then sometimes use this to define the function on overlapping neighborhoods, and continue this process along paths in the domain.
[src:complex-analysis/analytic-function] Analytic continuation is unique when it exists on a connected domain.
[src:complex-analysis/analytic-function] More precisely, if two analytic functions on a connected open set agree on a nonempty open subset, or more generally on a set having an accumulation point in the domain, then they agree everywhere on that connected open set.
[src:complex-analysis/analytic-function] However, analytic continuation need not be possible everywhere, and it need not be single-valued.
[src:complex-analysis/analytic-function] For example, the natural logarithm is locally analytic on $\mathbb {C} \setminus \{0\}$ , but continuation around a closed path encircling 0 changes its value by an integer multiple of $2\pi i$ .
[src:complex-analysis/analytic-function] For this reason, a single-valued branch of the logarithm can be defined on domains such as $\mathbb {C} \setminus (-\infty ,0]$ , but not on all of $\mathbb {C} \setminus \{0\}$ .
[src:complex-analysis/analytic-function] Taking a single analytic function in a disc and forming all possible analytic continuations of it leads in general to a Riemann surface that covers an open subset of the Riemann sphere.
[src:complex-analysis/analytic-function] The global analytic function obtained in this way is naturally a sheaf rather than a function: each germ is a convergent power series in some disc, but multiple germs may be stacked on top of each other.
[src:complex-analysis/analytic-function] Algebraic functions give another source of multi-valued analytic continuation.
[src:complex-analysis/analytic-function] For example, the function $f(z)={\sqrt {1-z}}$ is analytic, where the branch is such that $f(0)=1$ , has a convergent power series in the disc $|z|<1$ .
[src:complex-analysis/analytic-function] It can be continued around a loop enclosing $z=1$ , but transforms to its negative after a single loop.
[src:complex-analysis/analytic-function] The Riemann surface associated with an algebraic function is a finite ramified cover of the Riemann sphere.
[src:complex-analysis/analytic-function] Many special functions are first defined by a power series or an integral formula on a restricted domain and then extended by analytic continuation.
[src:complex-analysis/analytic-function] For example, the Riemann zeta function is initially defined by the Dirichlet series $\zeta (s)=\sum _{n=1}^{\infty }{\frac {1}{n^{s}}}$ for $\operatorname {Re} (s)>1$ , but it has a meromorphic continuation to the complex plane, with a single simple pole at $s=1$ .
[src:complex-analysis/analytic-function] One can define analytic functions in several variables by means of power series in those variables (see *Power series*).
[src:complex-analysis/analytic-function] Analytic functions of several variables have some of the same properties as analytic functions of one variable.
[src:complex-analysis/analytic-function] Analogous notions of analyticity can be formulated over other complete valued fields, the real and complex numbers being the two most prominent ones where the absolute value is archimedean.
[src:complex-analysis/analytic-function] Analytic functions can also be defined over non-Archimedean local fields, such as the p-adic numbers $\mathbb {Q} _{p}$ and its finite extension fields, and fields of formal Laurent series $\mathbb {F} _{q}((t))$ over a finite field.
[src:complex-analysis/analytic-function] If K is a complete valued field, a function on a neighborhood of a point $a\in K$ is called analytic if it is locally represented by a convergent power series $\sum _{n=0}^{\infty }c_{n}(x-a)^{n}$ with coefficients in K .
[src:complex-analysis/analytic-function] In the non-Archimedean case, convergence is governed by an ultrametric absolute value, and the resulting theory differs significantly from both real and complex analysis.
[src:complex-analysis/analytic-function] Over a non-Archimedean field the ring of analytic functions on a closed disc is thus related to the Tate algebra, the algebra of power series whose coefficients tend to zero sufficiently fast.
[src:complex-analysis/analytic-function] This point of view is fundamental in rigid analytic geometry and other forms of non-Archimedean analytic geometry.
[src:complex-analysis/cauchy-s-integral-theorem] In mathematics, the **Cauchy integral theorem** (also known as the **CauchyÔÇôGoursat theorem**) in complex analysis, named after Augustin-Louis Cauchy (and ├ëdouard Goursat), is an important statement about line integrals for holomorphic functions in the complex plane.
[src:complex-analysis/cauchy-s-integral-theorem] Also, when Ôüá $f(z)$ Ôüá has a single-valued antiderivative in an open region Ôüá U Ôüá, then the path integral Ôüá $\textstyle \int _{\gamma }f(z)\,dz$ Ôüá is path independent for all paths in Ôüá U Ôüá.
[src:complex-analysis/cauchy-s-integral-theorem] Let $U\subseteq \mathbb {C}$ be a simply connected open set, and let $f:U\to \mathbb {C}$ be a holomorphic function.
[src:complex-analysis/cauchy-s-integral-theorem] Let ${\displaystyle \gamma$ be a smooth closed curve.
[src:complex-analysis/cauchy-s-integral-theorem] Let $U\subseteq \mathbb {C}$ be an open set, and let $f:U\to \mathbb {C}$ be a holomorphic function.
[src:complex-analysis/cauchy-s-integral-theorem] If $\gamma$ is homotopic to a constant curve, then: $\int _{\gamma }f(z)\,dz=0,$ where Ôüá $z\in U$ Ôüá.
[src:complex-analysis/cauchy-s-integral-theorem] (Recall that a curve is homotopic to a constant curve if there exists a smooth homotopy (within U ) from the curve to the constant curve.
[src:complex-analysis/cauchy-s-integral-theorem] Intuitively, this means that one can shrink the curve into a point without exiting the space.) The first version is a special case of this because on a simply connected set, every closed curve is homotopic to a constant curve.
[src:complex-analysis/cauchy-s-integral-theorem] In both cases, it is important to remember that the curve $\gamma$ does not surround any "holes" in the domain, or else the theorem does not apply.
[src:complex-analysis/cauchy-s-integral-theorem] A famous example is the following curve: $\gamma (t)=e^{it}\quad t\in \left[0,2\pi \right],$ which traces out the unit circle.
[src:complex-analysis/cauchy-s-integral-theorem] Here the following integral: $\int _{\gamma }{\frac {1}{z}}\,dz=2\pi i\neq 0,$ is nonzero.
[src:complex-analysis/cauchy-s-integral-theorem] The Cauchy integral theorem does not apply here since $f(z)=1/z$ is not defined at Ôüá $z=0$ Ôüá.
[src:complex-analysis/cauchy-s-integral-theorem] Intuitively, $\gamma$ surrounds a "hole" in the domain of Ôüá f Ôüá, so $\gamma$ cannot be shrunk to a point without exiting the space.
[src:complex-analysis/cauchy-s-integral-theorem] As ├ëdouard Goursat showed, Cauchy's integral theorem can be proven assuming only that the complex derivative $f'(z)$ exists everywhere in Ôüá U Ôüá.
[src:complex-analysis/cauchy-s-integral-theorem] This is significant because one can then prove Cauchy's integral formula for these functions, and from that deduce these functions are infinitely differentiable.
[src:complex-analysis/cauchy-s-integral-theorem] The condition that U be simply connected means that U has no "holes" or, in homotopy terms, that the fundamental group of U is trivial; for instance, every open disk Ôüá $U_{z_{0}}=\{z:\left\vert z-z_{0}\right\vert <r\}$ Ôüá, for Ôüá $z_{0}\in \mathbb {C}$ Ôüá, qualifies.
[src:complex-analysis/cauchy-s-integral-theorem] The Cauchy integral theorem leads to Cauchy's integral formula and the residue theorem.
[src:complex-analysis/cauchy-s-integral-theorem] Cauchy provided this proof, but it was later proven by Goursat without requiring techniques from vector calculus, or the continuity of partial derivatives.
[src:complex-analysis/complex-analysis] At first glance, complex analysis is the study of holomorphic functions that are the differentiable functions of a complex variable.
[src:complex-analysis/complex-analysis] By contrast with the real case, a holomorphic function is always infinitely differentiable and equal to the sum of its Taylor series in some neighborhood of each point of its domain.
[src:complex-analysis/complex-analysis] This makes methods and results of complex analysis significantly different from that of real analysis.
[src:complex-analysis/complex-analysis] Complex functions also behave very differently under contour integration: the integral of a holomorphic function over a contour in the complex plane does not depend on the details of the contour, only how it winds around the singularities of the function.
[src:complex-analysis/complex-analysis] Being able to move a given contour to a more suitable one often leads to major simplifications in proofs.
[src:complex-analysis/complex-analysis] The theory of several complex variables generalizes one-variable complex function theory to more than one complex dimension.
[src:complex-analysis/complex-analysis] While many of the techniques of a single complex variable are used and generalized in this setting, several complex variables makes use of additional techniques such as Banach algebras and sheaf theory.
[src:complex-analysis/complex-analysis] Complex analysis is one of the classical branches in mathematics, with roots in the 18th century and just prior.
[src:complex-analysis/complex-analysis] Important mathematicians associated with complex numbers include Euler, Gauss, Riemann, Cauchy, Weierstrass, and many more in the 20th century.
[src:complex-analysis/complex-analysis] Complex analysis, in particular the theory of conformal mappings, has many physical applications and is also used throughout analytic number theory.
[src:complex-analysis/complex-analysis] In modern times, it has become very popular through a new boost from complex dynamics and the pictures of fractals produced by iterating holomorphic functions.
[src:complex-analysis/complex-analysis] Another important application of complex analysis is in string theory which examines conformal invariants in quantum field theory.
[src:complex-analysis/complex-analysis] A complex function is a function from complex numbers to complex numbers.
[src:complex-analysis/complex-analysis] In other words, it is a function that has a subset of the complex numbers as a domain and the complex numbers as a codomain.
[src:complex-analysis/complex-analysis] Complex functions are generally assumed to have a domain that contains a nonempty open subset of the complex plane.
[src:complex-analysis/complex-analysis] A complex function is continuous if and only if its associated vector-valued function of two variables is also continuous.
[src:complex-analysis/complex-analysis] However, this identification does not extend to differentiability.
[src:complex-analysis/complex-analysis] The definition of the derivative of a complex function is very similar to that of a real function, but the differentiability of the associated real function of two variables does not imply that the derivative of the complex function exists.
[src:complex-analysis/complex-analysis] In particular, if a complex function has a derivative, it has derivatives of every order and equals the sum of its Taylor series in a neighborhood of every point of its domain.
[src:complex-analysis/complex-analysis] It follows that two differentiable functions that are equal in a neighborhood of a point are equal on the intersection of their domain if the domains are connected.
[src:complex-analysis/complex-analysis] The latter property is the basis of the principle of analytic continuation which allows extending every real or complex analytic function in a unique way for getting a complex analytic function whose domain is the whole complex plane with a finite number of curve arcs removed.
[src:complex-analysis/complex-analysis] Many basic and special complex functions are defined in this way, including the complex exponential function, complex logarithm functions, and trigonometric functions.
[src:complex-analysis/complex-analysis] Complex functions that are differentiable at every point of an open subset $\Omega$ of the complex plane are said to be *holomorphic on* $\Omega$ .
[src:complex-analysis/complex-analysis] Superficially, this definition is formally analogous to that of the derivative of a real function.
[src:complex-analysis/complex-analysis] However, complex derivatives and differentiable functions behave in significantly different ways compared to their real counterparts.
[src:complex-analysis/complex-analysis] In particular, for this limit to exist, the value of the difference quotient must approach the same complex number, regardless of the manner in which we approach $z_{0}$ in the complex plane.
[src:complex-analysis/complex-analysis] Consequently, complex differentiability has much stronger implications than real differentiability.
[src:complex-analysis/complex-analysis] For instance, holomorphic functions are infinitely differentiable, whereas the existence of the *n*th derivative need not imply the existence of the (*n* + 1)th derivative for real functions.
[src:complex-analysis/complex-analysis] Furthermore, all holomorphic functions satisfy the stronger condition of analyticity, meaning that the function is, at every point in its domain, locally given by a convergent power series.
[src:complex-analysis/complex-analysis] In essence, this means that functions holomorphic on $\Omega$ can be approximated arbitrarily well by polynomials in some neighborhood of every point in $\Omega$ .
[src:complex-analysis/complex-analysis] This stands in sharp contrast to differentiable real functions; there are infinitely differentiable real functions that are *nowhere* analytic; see Non-analytic smooth function ┬º A smooth function which is nowhere real analytic.
[src:complex-analysis/complex-analysis] Such functions that are holomorphic everywhere except a set of isolated points are known as *meromorphic functions*.
[src:complex-analysis/complex-analysis] On the other hand, the functions $z\mapsto \Re (z)$ , $z\mapsto |z|$ , and $z\mapsto {\bar {z}}$ are not holomorphic anywhere on the complex plane, as can be shown by their failure to satisfy the CauchyÔÇôRiemann conditions (see below).
[src:complex-analysis/complex-analysis] An important property of holomorphic functions is the relationship between the partial derivatives of their real and imaginary components, known as the CauchyÔÇôRiemann conditions.
[src:complex-analysis/complex-analysis] In terms of the real and imaginary parts of the function, *u* and *v*, this is equivalent to the pair of equations $u_{x}=v_{y}$ and $u_{y}=-v_{x}$ , where the subscripts indicate partial differentiation.
[src:complex-analysis/complex-analysis] However, the CauchyÔÇôRiemann conditions do not characterize holomorphic functions, without additional continuity conditions (see LoomanÔÇôMenchoff theorem).
[src:complex-analysis/complex-analysis] Holomorphic functions exhibit some remarkable features.
[src:complex-analysis/complex-analysis] For instance, Picard's theorem asserts that the range of an entire function can take only three possible forms: $\mathbb {C}$ , $\mathbb {C} \setminus \{z_{0}\}$ , or $\{z_{0}\}$ for some $z_{0}\in \mathbb {C}$ .
[src:complex-analysis/complex-analysis] In other words, if two distinct complex numbers z and w are not in the range of an entire function f , then f is a constant function.
[src:complex-analysis/complex-analysis] Moreover, a holomorphic function on a connected open set is determined by its restriction to any nonempty open subset.
[src:complex-analysis/complex-analysis] In mathematics, a conformal map is a function that locally preserves angles, but not necessarily lengths.
[src:complex-analysis/complex-analysis] More formally, let U and V be open subsets of $\mathbb {R} ^{n}$ .
[src:complex-analysis/complex-analysis] A function $f:U\to V$ is called conformal (or angle-preserving) at a point $u_{0}\in U$ if it preserves angles between directed curves through $u_{0}$ , as well as preserving orientation.
[src:complex-analysis/complex-analysis] Conformal maps preserve both angles and the shapes of infinitesimally small figures, but not necessarily their size or curvature.
[src:complex-analysis/complex-analysis] The conformal property may be described in terms of the Jacobian derivative matrix of a coordinate transformation.
[src:complex-analysis/complex-analysis] The transformation is conformal whenever the Jacobian at each point is a positive scalar times a rotation matrix (orthogonal with determinant one).
[src:complex-analysis/complex-analysis] Some authors define conformality to include orientation-reversing mappings whose Jacobians can be written as any scalar times any orthogonal matrix.
[src:complex-analysis/complex-analysis] For mappings in two dimensions, the (orientation-preserving) conformal mappings are precisely the locally invertible complex analytic functions.
[src:complex-analysis/complex-analysis] In three and higher dimensions, Liouville's theorem sharply limits the conformal mappings to a few types.
[src:complex-analysis/complex-analysis] The notion of conformality generalizes in a natural way to maps between Riemannian or semi-Riemannian manifolds.
[src:complex-analysis/complex-analysis] One of the central tools in complex analysis is the line integral.
[src:complex-analysis/complex-analysis] The line integral around a closed path of a function that is holomorphic everywhere inside the area bounded by the closed path is always zero, as is stated by the Cauchy integral theorem.
[src:complex-analysis/complex-analysis] The values of such a holomorphic function inside a disk can be computed by a path integral on the disk's boundary (as shown in Cauchy's integral formula).
[src:complex-analysis/complex-analysis] Path integrals in the complex plane are often used to determine complicated real integrals, and here the theory of residues among others is applicable (see methods of contour integration).
[src:complex-analysis/complex-analysis] A "pole" (or isolated singularity) of a function is a point where the function's value becomes unbounded, or "blows up".
[src:complex-analysis/complex-analysis] If a function has such a pole, then one can compute the function's residue there, which can be used to compute path integrals involving the function; this is the content of the powerful residue theorem.
[src:complex-analysis/complex-analysis] The remarkable behavior of holomorphic functions near essential singularities is described by Picard's theorem.
[src:complex-analysis/complex-analysis] Functions that have only poles but no essential singularities are called meromorphic.
[src:complex-analysis/complex-analysis] Laurent series are the complex-valued equivalent to Taylor series, but can be used to study the behavior of functions near singularities through infinite sums of more well understood functions, such as polynomials.
[src:complex-analysis/complex-analysis] A bounded function that is holomorphic in the entire complex plane must be constant; this is Liouville's theorem.
[src:complex-analysis/complex-analysis] It can be used to provide a natural and short proof for the fundamental theorem of algebra which states that the field of complex numbers is algebraically closed.
[src:complex-analysis/complex-analysis] If a function is holomorphic throughout a connected domain then its values are fully determined by its values on any smaller subdomain.
[src:complex-analysis/complex-analysis] The function on the larger domain is said to be analytically continued from its values on the smaller domain.
[src:complex-analysis/complex-analysis] This allows the extension of the definition of functions, such as the Riemann zeta function, which are initially defined in terms of infinite sums that converge only on limited domains to almost the entire complex plane.
[src:complex-analysis/complex-analysis] Sometimes, as in the case of the natural logarithm, it is impossible to analytically continue a holomorphic function to a non-simply connected domain in the complex plane but it is possible to extend it to a holomorphic function on a closely related surface known as a Riemann surface.
[src:complex-analysis/complex-analysis] All this refers to complex analysis in one variable.
[src:complex-analysis/complex-analysis] There is also a very rich theory of complex analysis in more than one complex dimension in which the analytic properties such as power series expansion carry over whereas most of the geometric properties of holomorphic functions in one complex dimension (such as conformality) do not carry over.
[src:complex-analysis/complex-analysis] The Riemann mapping theorem about the conformal relationship of certain domains in the complex plane, which may be the most important result in the one-dimensional theory, fails dramatically in higher dimensions.
[src:complex-analysis/complex-analysis] A major application of certain complex spaces is in quantum mechanics as wave functions.
[src:complex-analysis/conformal-map] In mathematics, a **conformal map** is a function that locally preserves angles, but not necessarily lengths.
[src:complex-analysis/conformal-map] A function $f:U\to V$ is called **conformal** (or **angle-preserving**) at a point $u_{0}\in U$ if it preserves angles between directed curves through $u_{0}$ , as well as preserving orientation.
[src:complex-analysis/conformal-map] If U is an open subset of the complex plane $\mathbb {C}$ , then a function $f:U\to \mathbb {C}$ is conformal if and only if it is holomorphic and its derivative is everywhere non-zero on U .
[src:complex-analysis/conformal-map] If f is antiholomorphic (complex conjugate to a holomorphic function), it preserves angles but reverses their orientation.
[src:complex-analysis/conformal-map] In the literature, there is another definition of conformal: a mapping f which is one-to-one and holomorphic on an open set in the plane.
[src:complex-analysis/conformal-map] The open mapping theorem forces the inverse function (defined on the image of f ) to be holomorphic.
[src:complex-analysis/conformal-map] Thus, under this definition, a map is conformal if and only if it is biholomorphic.
[src:complex-analysis/conformal-map] The two definitions for conformal maps are not equivalent.
[src:complex-analysis/conformal-map] Being one-to-one and holomorphic implies having a non-zero derivative.
[src:complex-analysis/conformal-map] However, the exponential function is a holomorphic function with a nonzero derivative, but is not one-to-one since it is periodic.
[src:complex-analysis/conformal-map] The Riemann mapping theorem, one of the profound results of complex analysis, states that any non-empty open simply connected proper subset of $\mathbb {C}$ admits a bijective conformal map to the open unit disk in $\mathbb {C}$ .
[src:complex-analysis/conformal-map] Informally, this means that any blob can be transformed into a perfect disk by some conformal map.
[src:complex-analysis/conformal-map] A map of the Riemann sphere onto itself is conformal if and only if it is a M├Âbius transformation.
[src:complex-analysis/conformal-map] The complex conjugate of a M├Âbius transformation preserves angles, but reverses the orientation.
[src:complex-analysis/conformal-map] In plane geometry there are three types of angles that may be preserved in a conformal map.
[src:complex-analysis/conformal-map] Each is hosted by its own real algebra, ordinary complex numbers, split-complex numbers, and dual numbers.
[src:complex-analysis/conformal-map] The conformal maps are described by linear fractional transformations in each case.
[src:complex-analysis/conformal-map] In Riemannian geometry, two Riemannian metrics g and h on a smooth manifold M are called **conformally equivalent** if $g=uh$ for some positive function u on M .
[src:complex-analysis/conformal-map] The function ${\sqrt {u}}$ is called the **conformal factor**.
[src:complex-analysis/conformal-map] A diffeomorphism between two Riemannian manifolds is called a **conformal map** if the pulled back metric is conformally equivalent to the original one.
[src:complex-analysis/conformal-map] For example, stereographic projection of a sphere onto the plane augmented with a point at infinity is a conformal map.
[src:complex-analysis/conformal-map] One can also define a **conformal structure** on a smooth manifold, as a class of conformally equivalent Riemannian metrics.
[src:complex-analysis/conformal-map] A classical theorem of Joseph Liouville shows that there are far fewer conformal maps in higher dimensions than in two dimensions.
[src:complex-analysis/conformal-map] Any conformal map from an open subset of Euclidean space into the same Euclidean space of dimension three or greater can be composed from three types of transformations: a homothety, an isometry, and a special conformal transformation.
[src:complex-analysis/conformal-map] For linear transformations, a conformal map may only be composed of homothety and isometry, and is called a conformal linear transformation.
[src:complex-analysis/conformal-map] Applications of conformal mapping exist in aerospace engineering, in biomedical sciences (including brain mapping and genetic mapping), in applied math (for geodesics and in geometry), in earth sciences (including geophysics, geography, and cartography), in engineering, and in electronics.
[src:complex-analysis/conformal-map] In cartography, several named map projections, including the Mercator projection and the stereographic projection are conformal.
[src:complex-analysis/conformal-map] The preservation of compass directions makes them useful in marine navigation.
[src:complex-analysis/conformal-map] Conformal mappings are invaluable for solving problems in engineering and physics that can be expressed in terms of functions of a complex variable yet exhibit inconvenient geometries.
[src:complex-analysis/conformal-map] By choosing an appropriate mapping, the analyst can transform the inconvenient geometry into a much more convenient one.
[src:complex-analysis/conformal-map] For example, one may wish to calculate the electric field, $E(z)$ , arising from a point charge located near the corner of two conducting planes separated by a certain angle (where z is the complex coordinate of a point in 2-space).
[src:complex-analysis/conformal-map] This problem *per se* is quite clumsy to solve in closed form.
[src:complex-analysis/conformal-map] However, by employing a very simple conformal mapping, the inconvenient angle is mapped to one of precisely $\pi$ radians, meaning that the corner of two planes is transformed to a straight line.
[src:complex-analysis/conformal-map] In this new domain, the problem (that of calculating the electric field impressed by a point charge located near a conducting wall) is quite easy to solve.
[src:complex-analysis/conformal-map] The solution is obtained in this domain, $E(w)$ , and then mapped back to the original domain by noting that w was obtained as a function (*viz*., the composition of E and w ) of z , whence $E(w)$ can be viewed as $E(w(z))$ , which is a function of z , the original coordinate basis.
[src:complex-analysis/conformal-map] Note that this application is not a contradiction to the fact that conformal mappings preserve angles, they do so only for points in the interior of their domain, and not at the boundary.
[src:complex-analysis/conformal-map] Another example is the application of conformal mapping technique for solving the boundary value problem of liquid sloshing in tanks.
[src:complex-analysis/conformal-map] If a function is harmonic (that is, it satisfies Laplace's equation $\nabla ^{2}f=0$ ) over a plane domain (which is two-dimensional), and is transformed via a conformal map to another plane domain, the transformation is also harmonic.
[src:complex-analysis/conformal-map] For this reason, any function which is defined by a potential can be transformed by a conformal map and still remain governed by a potential.
[src:complex-analysis/conformal-map] Examples in physics of equations defined by a potential include the electromagnetic field, the gravitational field, and, in fluid dynamics, potential flow, which is an approximation to fluid flow assuming constant density, zero viscosity, and irrotational flow.
[src:complex-analysis/conformal-map] One example of a fluid dynamic application of a conformal map is the Joukowsky transform that can be used to examine the field of flow around a Joukowsky airfoil.
[src:complex-analysis/conformal-map] Conformal maps are also valuable in solving nonlinear partial differential equations in some specific geometries.
[src:complex-analysis/conformal-map] Such analytic solutions provide a useful check on the accuracy of numerical simulations of the governing equation.
[src:complex-analysis/conformal-map] For example, in the case of very viscous free-surface flow around a semi-infinite wall, the domain can be mapped to a half-plane in which the solution is one-dimensional and straightforward to calculate.
[src:complex-analysis/conformal-map] For discrete systems, Noury and Yang presented a way to convert discrete systems root locus into continuous root locus through a well-known conformal mapping in geometry (aka inversion mapping).
[src:complex-analysis/conformal-map] Maxwell's equations are preserved by Lorentz transformations which form a group including circular and hyperbolic rotations.
[src:complex-analysis/conformal-map] The latter are sometimes called Lorentz boosts to distinguish them from circular rotations.
[src:complex-analysis/conformal-map] All these transformations are conformal since hyperbolic rotations preserve hyperbolic angle, (called rapidity) and the other rotations preserve circular angle.
[src:complex-analysis/conformal-map] The introduction of translations in the Poincar├® group again preserves angles.
[src:complex-analysis/conformal-map] A larger group of conformal maps for relating solutions of Maxwell's equations was identified by Ebenezer Cunningham (1908) and Harry Bateman (1910).
[src:complex-analysis/conformal-map] Their training at Cambridge University had given them facility with the method of image charges and associated methods of images for spheres and inversion.
[src:complex-analysis/conformal-map] Warwick highlights this "new theorem of relativity" as a Cambridge response to Einstein, and as founded on exercises using the method of inversion, such as found in James Hopwood Jeans textbook *Mathematical Theory of Electricity and Magnetism*.
[src:complex-analysis/conformal-map] In general relativity, conformal maps are the simplest and thus most common type of causal transformations.
[src:complex-analysis/conformal-map] It is often used to try to make models amenable to extension beyond curvature singularities, for example to permit description of the universe even before the Big Bang.
[src:complex-analysis/holomorphic-function] In mathematics, a **holomorphic function** is a complex-valued function of one or more complex variables that is complex differentiable in a neighbourhood of each point in a domain in complex coordinate space Ôüá $\mathbb {C} ^{n}$ Ôüá.
[src:complex-analysis/holomorphic-function] The existence of a complex derivative in a neighbourhood is a very strong condition: It implies that a holomorphic function is infinitely differentiable and locally equal to its own Taylor series (is *analytic*).
[src:complex-analysis/holomorphic-function] Holomorphic functions are the central objects of study in complex analysis.
[src:complex-analysis/holomorphic-function] That all holomorphic functions are complex analytic functions, and vice versa, is a major theorem in complex analysis.
[src:complex-analysis/holomorphic-function] Holomorphic functions are also sometimes referred to as *regular functions*.
[src:complex-analysis/holomorphic-function] A holomorphic function whose domain is the whole complex plane is called an entire function.
[src:complex-analysis/holomorphic-function] The phrase "holomorphic at a point Ôüá $z_{0}$ Ôüá" means not just differentiable at Ôüá $z_{0}$ Ôüá, but differentiable everywhere within some close neighbourhood of Ôüá $z_{0}$ Ôüá in the complex plane.
[src:complex-analysis/holomorphic-function] This is the same definition as for the derivative of a real function, except that all quantities are complex.
[src:complex-analysis/holomorphic-function] In particular, the limit is taken as the complex number Ôüá z Ôüá tends to Ôüá $z_{0}$ Ôüá, and this means that the same value is obtained for any sequence of complex values for Ôüá z Ôüá that tends to Ôüá $z_{0}$ Ôüá.
[src:complex-analysis/holomorphic-function] If the limit exists, Ôüá f Ôüá is said to be **complex differentiable** at Ôüá $z_{0}$ Ôüá.
[src:complex-analysis/holomorphic-function] This concept of complex differentiability shares several properties with real differentiability: It is linear and obeys the product rule, quotient rule, and chain rule.
[src:complex-analysis/holomorphic-function] A function is **holomorphic** on an open set Ôüá U Ôüá if it is *complex differentiable* at *every* point of Ôüá U Ôüá.
[src:complex-analysis/holomorphic-function] A function Ôüá f Ôüá is *holomorphic* at a point Ôüá $z_{0}$ Ôüá if it is holomorphic on some neighbourhood of Ôüá $z_{0}$ Ôüá.
[src:complex-analysis/holomorphic-function] A function is *holomorphic* on some non-open set Ôüá A Ôüá if it is holomorphic at every point of Ôüá A Ôüá.
[src:complex-analysis/holomorphic-function] A function may be complex differentiable at a point but not holomorphic at this point.
[src:complex-analysis/holomorphic-function] For example, the function Ôüá $\textstyle f(z)=\vert z\vert {\vphantom {l}}^{2}=z{\bar {z}}$ Ôüá *is* complex differentiable at Ôüá 0 Ôüá, but *is not* complex differentiable anywhere else, especially including in no place close to Ôüá 0 Ôüá (see the CauchyÔÇôRiemann equations, below).
[src:complex-analysis/holomorphic-function] which is to say that, roughly, Ôüá f Ôüá is functionally independent from Ôüá ${\bar {z}}$ Ôüá, the complex conjugate of Ôüá z Ôüá.
[src:complex-analysis/holomorphic-function] If continuity is not given, the converse is not necessarily true.
[src:complex-analysis/holomorphic-function] A simple converse is that if Ôüá u Ôüá and Ôüá v Ôüá have *continuous* first partial derivatives and satisfy the CauchyÔÇôRiemann equations, then Ôüá f Ôüá is holomorphic.
[src:complex-analysis/holomorphic-function] A more satisfying converse, which is much harder to prove, is the LoomanÔÇôMenchoff theorem: if Ôüá f Ôüá is continuous, Ôüá u Ôüá and Ôüá v Ôüá have first partial derivatives (but not necessarily continuous), and they satisfy the CauchyÔÇôRiemann equations, then Ôüá f Ôüá is holomorphic.
[src:complex-analysis/holomorphic-function] An immediate useful consequence of the CauchyÔÇôRiemann equations above is that the complex derivative can be defined explicitly in terms of real partial derivatives.
[src:complex-analysis/holomorphic-function] A holomorphic function resembles an entire function ("whole") in a domain of the complex plane while a meromorphic function (defined to mean holomorphic except at certain isolated poles), resembles a rational fraction ("part") of entire functions in a domain of the complex plane.
[src:complex-analysis/holomorphic-function] Cauchy had instead used the term *synectic*.
[src:complex-analysis/holomorphic-function] Today, the term "holomorphic function" is sometimes preferred to "analytic function".
[src:complex-analysis/holomorphic-function] An important result in complex analysis is that every holomorphic function is complex analytic, a fact that does not follow obviously from the definitions.
[src:complex-analysis/holomorphic-function] The term "analytic" is however also in wide use.
[src:complex-analysis/holomorphic-function] Because complex differentiation is linear and obeys the product, quotient, and chain rules, the sums, products and compositions of holomorphic functions are holomorphic, and the quotient of two holomorphic functions is holomorphic wherever the denominator is not zero.
[src:complex-analysis/holomorphic-function] That is, if functions Ôüá f Ôüá and Ôüá g Ôüá are holomorphic in a domain Ôüá U Ôüá, then so are Ôüá $f+g$ Ôüá, Ôüá $f-g$ Ôüá, Ôüá $fg$ Ôüá, and Ôüá $f\circ g$ Ôüá.
[src:complex-analysis/holomorphic-function] Furthermore, Ôüá $f/g$ Ôüá is holomorphic if Ôüá g Ôüá has no zeros in Ôüá U Ôüá; otherwise it is meromorphic.
[src:complex-analysis/holomorphic-function] If one identifies Ôüá $\mathbb {C}$ Ôüá with the real plane Ôüá $\textstyle \mathbb {R} ^{2}$ Ôüá, then the holomorphic functions coincide with those functions of two real variables with continuous first derivatives which solve the CauchyÔÇôRiemann equations, a set of two partial differential equations.
[src:complex-analysis/holomorphic-function] Conversely, every harmonic function Ôüá $u(x,y)$ Ôüá on a simply connected domain Ôüá $\textstyle \Omega \subset \mathbb {R} ^{2}$ Ôüá is the real part of a holomorphic function: If Ôüá v Ôüá is the harmonic conjugate of Ôüá u Ôüá, unique up to a constant, then Ôüá $f(x+iy)=u(x,y)+i\,v(x,y)$ Ôüá is holomorphic.
[src:complex-analysis/holomorphic-function] Here Ôüá $\gamma$ Ôüá is a rectifiable path in a simply connected complex domain Ôüá $U\subset \mathbb {C}$ Ôüá whose start point is equal to its end point, and Ôüá $f\colon U\to \mathbb {C}$ Ôüá is a holomorphic function.
[src:complex-analysis/holomorphic-function] Cauchy's integral formula states that every function holomorphic inside a disk is completely determined by its values on the disk's boundary.
[src:complex-analysis/holomorphic-function] Furthermore: Suppose Ôüá $U\subset \mathbb {C}$ Ôüá is a complex domain, Ôüá $f\colon U\to \mathbb {C}$ Ôüá is a holomorphic function and the closed disk Ôüá $D\equiv \{z:\vert z-z_{0}\vert \leq r\}$ Ôüá is completely contained in Ôüá U Ôüá.
[src:complex-analysis/holomorphic-function] Let Ôüá $\gamma$ Ôüá be the circle forming the boundary of Ôüá D Ôüá.
[src:complex-analysis/holomorphic-function] where the contour integral is taken counter-clockwise.
[src:complex-analysis/holomorphic-function] for infinitesimal positive loops Ôüá $\gamma$ Ôüá around Ôüá a Ôüá.
[src:complex-analysis/holomorphic-function] In regions where the first derivative is not zero, holomorphic functions are conformal: they preserve angles and the shape (but not size) of small figures.
[src:complex-analysis/holomorphic-function] That is, a holomorphic function Ôüá f Ôüá has derivatives of every order at each point Ôüá a Ôüá in its domain, and it coincides with its own Taylor series at Ôüá a Ôüá in a neighbourhood of Ôüá a Ôüá.
[src:complex-analysis/holomorphic-function] In fact, Ôüá f Ôüá coincides with its Taylor series at Ôüá a Ôüá in any disk centred at that point and lying within the domain of the function.
[src:complex-analysis/holomorphic-function] From an algebraic point of view, the set of holomorphic functions on an open set is a commutative ring and a complex vector space.
[src:complex-analysis/holomorphic-function] Additionally, the set of holomorphic functions in an open set Ôüá U Ôüá is an integral domain if and only if the open set Ôüá U Ôüá is connected.
[src:complex-analysis/holomorphic-function] In fact, it is a locally convex topological vector space, with the seminorms being the suprema on compact subsets.
[src:complex-analysis/holomorphic-function] From a geometric perspective, a function Ôüá f Ôüá is holomorphic at Ôüá $z_{0}$ Ôüá if and only if its exterior derivative Ôüá $\mathrm {d} f$ Ôüá in a neighbourhood Ôüá U Ôüá of Ôüá $z_{0}$ Ôüá is equal to Ôüá $f'(z)\,\mathrm {d} z$ Ôüá for some continuous function Ôüá $f'$ Ôüá.
[src:complex-analysis/holomorphic-function] that Ôüá $\mathrm {d} f'$ Ôüá is also proportional to Ôüá $\mathrm {d} z$ Ôüá, implying that the derivative Ôüá $\mathrm {d} f'$ Ôüá is itself holomorphic and thus that Ôüá f Ôüá is infinitely differentiable.
[src:complex-analysis/holomorphic-function] Similarly, Ôüá $\mathrm {d} (f\,\mathrm {d} z)=f'\,\mathrm {d} z\wedge \mathrm {d} z=0$ Ôüá implies that any function Ôüá f Ôüá that is holomorphic on the simply connected region Ôüá U Ôüá is also integrable on Ôüá U Ôüá.
[src:complex-analysis/holomorphic-function] The principal branch of the complex logarithm function Ôüá $\log z$ Ôüá is holomorphic on the domain Ôüá $\mathbb {C} \smallsetminus \{z\in \mathbb {R} :z\leq 0\}$ Ôüá.
[src:complex-analysis/holomorphic-function] The square root function can be defined as Ôüá ${\sqrt {z}}\equiv \exp {\bigl (}{\tfrac {1}{2}}\log z{\bigr )}$ Ôüá and is therefore holomorphic wherever the logarithm Ôüá $\log z$ Ôüá is.
[src:complex-analysis/holomorphic-function] The reciprocal function Ôüá ${\tfrac {1}{z}}$ Ôüá is holomorphic on Ôüá $\mathbb {C} \smallsetminus \{0\}$ Ôüá.
[src:complex-analysis/holomorphic-function] As a consequence of the CauchyÔÇôRiemann equations, any real-valued holomorphic function must be constant.
[src:complex-analysis/holomorphic-function] Therefore, the absolute value Ôüá $\vert z\vert$ Ôüá, the argument Ôüá $\arg z$ Ôüá, the real part Ôüá $\operatorname {Re} (z)$ Ôüá and the imaginary part Ôüá $\operatorname {Im} (z)$ Ôüá are not holomorphic.
[src:complex-analysis/holomorphic-function] Another typical example of a continuous function which is not holomorphic is the complex conjugate Ôüá ${\bar {z}}$ Ôüá.
[src:complex-analysis/holomorphic-function] The definition of a holomorphic function generalizes to several complex variables in a straightforward way.
[src:complex-analysis/holomorphic-function] The much deeper Hartogs' theorem proves that the continuity assumption is unnecessary: Ôüá f Ôüá is holomorphic if and only if it is holomorphic in each variable separately.
[src:complex-analysis/holomorphic-function] More generally, a function of several complex variables that is square integrable over every compact subset of its domain is analytic if and only if it satisfies the CauchyÔÇôRiemann equations in the sense of distributions.
[src:complex-analysis/holomorphic-function] Functions of several complex variables are in some basic ways more complicated than functions of a single complex variable.
[src:complex-analysis/holomorphic-function] For example, the region of convergence of a power series is not necessarily an open ball; these regions are logarithmically convex Reinhardt domains, the simplest example of which is a polydisk.
[src:complex-analysis/holomorphic-function] However, they also come with some fundamental restrictions.
[src:complex-analysis/holomorphic-function] Unlike functions of a single complex variable, the possible domains on which there are holomorphic functions that cannot be extended to larger domains are highly limited.
[src:complex-analysis/holomorphic-function] Such a set is called a domain of holomorphy.
[src:complex-analysis/holomorphic-function] A complex differential Ôüá $(p,0)$ Ôüá-form Ôüá $\alpha$ Ôüá is holomorphic if and only if its antiholomorphic Dolbeault derivative is zero: Ôüá ${\bar {\partial }}\alpha =0$ Ôüá.
[src:complex-analysis/holomorphic-function] The concept of a holomorphic function can be extended to the infinite-dimensional spaces of functional analysis.
[src:complex-analysis/holomorphic-function] For instance, the Fr├®chet or Gateaux derivative can be used to define a notion of a holomorphic function on a Banach space over the field of complex numbers.
[src:complex-analysis/laurent-series] In mathematics, the **Laurent series** of a complex function $f(z)$ is a representation of that function as a power series which includes terms of negative degree.
[src:complex-analysis/laurent-series] It may be used to express complex functions in cases where a Taylor series expansion cannot be applied.
[src:complex-analysis/laurent-series] The Laurent series was named after and first published by Pierre Alphonse Laurent in 1843.
[src:complex-analysis/laurent-series] Karl Weierstrass had previously described it in a paper written in 1841 but not published until 1894.
[src:complex-analysis/laurent-series] The path of integration $\gamma$ is counterclockwise around a Jordan curve enclosing c and lying in an annulus A in which $f(z)$ is holomorphic (analytic).
[src:complex-analysis/laurent-series] The expansion for $f(z)$ will then be valid anywhere inside the annulus.
[src:complex-analysis/laurent-series] The annulus is shown in red in the figure on the right, along with an example of a suitable path of integration labeled $\gamma$ .
[src:complex-analysis/laurent-series] When $\gamma$ is defined as the circle $|z-c|=\varrho$ , where $r<\varrho <R$ , this amounts to computing the complex Fourier coefficients of the restriction of f to $\gamma$ .
[src:complex-analysis/laurent-series] The fact that these integrals are unchanged by a deformation of the contour $\gamma$ is an immediate consequence of Cauchy's integral theorem.
[src:complex-analysis/laurent-series] One may also obtain the Laurent series for a complex function $f(z)$ at $z=\infty$ .
[src:complex-analysis/laurent-series] However, this is the same as when $R\rightarrow \infty$ .
[src:complex-analysis/laurent-series] The above integral formula may not offer the most practical method for computing the coefficients $a_{n}$ for a given function $f(z)$ ; instead, one often pieces together the Laurent series by combining known Taylor expansions.
[src:complex-analysis/laurent-series] Because the Laurent expansion of a function is unique whenever it exists, any expression of this form that equals the given function $f(z)$ in some annulus must actually be the Laurent expansion of $f(z)$ .
[src:complex-analysis/laurent-series] Laurent series with complex coefficients are an important tool in complex analysis, especially to investigate the behavior of functions near singularities.
[src:complex-analysis/laurent-series] As a real function, it is infinitely differentiable everywhere; as a complex function however it is not differentiable at $x=0$ .
[src:complex-analysis/laurent-series] The Laurent series of $f(x)$ is obtained via the power series representation, $e^{-1/x^{2}}=\sum _{n=0}^{\infty }(-1)^{n}\,{x^{-2n} \over n!},$ which converges to $f(x)$ for all $x\in \mathbb {C}$ except at the singularity $x=0$ .
[src:complex-analysis/laurent-series] The graph on the right shows $f(x)$ in black and its Laurent approximations $\sum _{n=0}^{N}(-1)^{n}\,{x^{-2n} \over n!},\quad \forall N\in \mathbb {N} ^{+}.$ As $N\to \infty$ , the approximation becomes exact for all (complex) numbers x except at the singularity $x=0$ .
[src:complex-analysis/laurent-series] More generally, Laurent series can be used to express holomorphic functions defined on an annulus, much as power series are used to express holomorphic functions defined on a disc.
[src:complex-analysis/laurent-series] Suppose $\sum _{n=-\infty }^{\infty }a_{n}(z-c)^{n}$ is a given Laurent series with complex coefficients $a_{n}$ and a complex center c .
[src:complex-analysis/laurent-series] It is possible that r may be zero or R may be infinite; at the other extreme, it's not necessarily true that r is less than R .
[src:complex-analysis/laurent-series] When $r=0$ , the coefficient $a_{-1}$ of the Laurent expansion is called the **residue** of $f(z)$ at the singularity c .
[src:complex-analysis/laurent-series] For example, the function $f(z)={e^{z} \over z}+e^{{1}/{z}},$ is holomorphic everywhere except at $z=0$ .
[src:complex-analysis/laurent-series] Conversely, for a holomorphic function $f(z)$ defined on the annulus $A=\{z:r<|z-c|<R\}$ , there always exists a unique Laurent series with center c which converges (at least on A ) to $f(z)$ .
[src:complex-analysis/laurent-series] This function has singularities at $z=1$ and $z=2i$ , where the denominator is zero and the expression is therefore undefined.
[src:complex-analysis/laurent-series] A Taylor series about $z=0$ (which yields a power series) will only converge in a disc of radius 1, since it "hits" the singularity at $z=1$ .
[src:complex-analysis/laurent-series] The series converges uniformly on $r+\varepsilon \leq |z-c|\leq R-\varepsilon$ , where *╬Á* is a positive number small enough for *╬│* to be contained in the constricted closed annulus, so the integration and summation can be interchanged.
[src:complex-analysis/laurent-series] A **Laurent polynomial** is a Laurent series in which only finitely many coefficients are non-zero.
[src:complex-analysis/laurent-series] Laurent polynomials differ from ordinary polynomials in that they may have terms of negative degree.
[src:complex-analysis/laurent-series] If the principal part of f is a finite sum, then f has a pole at c of order equal to (negative) the degree of the highest term; on the other hand, if f has an essential singularity at c , the principal part is an infinite sum (meaning it has infinitely many non-zero terms).
[src:complex-analysis/laurent-series] If the inner radius of convergence of the Laurent series for f is 0, then f has an essential singularity at c if and only if the principal part is an infinite sum, and has a pole otherwise.
[src:complex-analysis/laurent-series] If the inner radius of convergence is positive, f may have infinitely many negative terms but still be regular at c , as in the example above, in which case it is represented by a *different* Laurent series in a disk about c .
[src:complex-analysis/laurent-series] Laurent series with only finitely many negative terms are well-behavedÔÇöthey are a power series divided by $z^{k}$ , and can be analyzed similarlyÔÇöwhile Laurent series with infinitely many negative terms have complicated behavior on the inner circle of convergence.
[src:complex-analysis/laurent-series] Laurent series cannot in general be multiplied.
[src:complex-analysis/laurent-series] Algebraically, the expression for the terms of the product may involve infinite sums which need not converge (one cannot take the convolution of integer sequences).
[src:complex-analysis/laurent-series] Geometrically, the two Laurent series may have non-overlapping annuli of convergence.
[src:complex-analysis/laurent-series] Two Laurent series with only *finitely* many negative terms can be multiplied: algebraically, the sums are all finite; geometrically, these have poles at c , and inner radius of convergence 0, so they both converge on an overlapping annulus.
[src:complex-analysis/laurent-series] Thus when defining formal Laurent series, one requires Laurent series with only finitely many negative terms.
[src:complex-analysis/laurent-series] Similarly, the sum of two convergent Laurent series need not converge, though it is always defined formally, but the sum of two bounded below Laurent series (or any Laurent series on a punctured disk) has a non-empty annulus of convergence.
[src:complex-analysis/laurent-series] Also, for a field F , by the sum and multiplication defined above, formal Laurent series would form a field $F((x))$ which is also the field of fractions of the ring $F[[x]]$ of formal power series.
[src:complex-analysis/residue-theorem] In complex analysis, the **residue theorem**, sometimes called **Cauchy's residue theorem**, is a powerful tool to evaluate line integrals of analytic functions over closed curves; it can often be used to compute real integrals and infinite series as well.
[src:complex-analysis/residue-theorem] It generalizes the Cauchy integral theorem and Cauchy's integral formula.
[src:complex-analysis/residue-theorem] The **residue theorem** should not be confused with special cases of the generalized Stokes' theorem; however, the latter can be used as a component of its proof.
[src:complex-analysis/residue-theorem] The relationship of the residue theorem to Stokes' theorem is given by the Jordan curve theorem.
[src:complex-analysis/residue-theorem] The general plane curve ╬│ must first be reduced to a set of simple closed curves $\{\gamma _{i}\}$ whose total is equivalent to $\gamma$ for integration purposes; this reduces the problem to finding the integral of $f\,dz$ along a Jordan curve $\gamma _{i}$ with interior Ôüá V Ôüá.
[src:complex-analysis/residue-theorem] The requirement that f be holomorphic on $U_{0}=U\smallsetminus \{a_{k}\}$ is equivalent to the statement that the exterior derivative $d(f\,dz)=0$ on Ôüá $U_{0}$ Ôüá.
[src:complex-analysis/residue-theorem] Thus if two planar regions V and W of U enclose the same subset $\{a_{j}\}$ of Ôüá $\{a_{k}\}$ Ôüá, the regions $V\smallsetminus W$ and $W\smallsetminus V$ lie entirely in Ôüá $U_{0}$ Ôüá, hence $\int _{V\smallsetminus W}d(f\,dz)-\int _{W\smallsetminus V}d(f\,dz)$ is well-defined and equal to zero.
[src:complex-analysis/residue-theorem] Consequently, the contour integral of $f\,dz$ along $\gamma _{j}=\partial V$ is equal to the sum of a set of integrals along paths Ôüá $\gamma _{j}$ Ôüá, each enclosing an arbitrarily small region around a single $a_{j}$ ÔÇö the residues of f (up to the conventional factor $2\pi i$ at Ôüá $\{a_{j}\}$ Ôüá.
[src:complex-analysis/residue-theorem] Summing over Ôüá $\{\gamma _{j}\}$ Ôüá, we recover the final expression of the contour integral in terms of the winding numbers Ôüá $\{\operatorname {I} (\gamma ,a_{k})\}$ Ôüá.
[src:complex-analysis/residue-theorem] The integral over this curve can then be computed using the residue theorem.
[src:complex-analysis/residue-theorem] Often, the half-circle part of the integral will tend towards zero as the radius of the half-circle grows, leaving only the real-axis part of the integral, the one we were originally interested in.
[src:complex-analysis/residue-theorem] Suppose a punctured disk Ôüá $D=\{z:0<\vert z-c\vert <R\}$ Ôüá in the complex plane is given and Ôüá f Ôüá is a holomorphic function defined (at least) on Ôüá D Ôüá.
[src:complex-analysis/residue-theorem] The residue Ôüá $\operatorname {Res} (f,c)$ Ôüá of Ôüá f Ôüá at Ôüá c Ôüá is the coefficient Ôüá $a_{-1}$ Ôüá of Ôüá $(z-c)^{-1}$ Ôüá in the Laurent series expansion of Ôüá f Ôüá around Ôüá c Ôüá.
[src:complex-analysis/residue-theorem] Various methods exist for calculating this value, and the choice of which method to use depends on the function in question, and on the nature of the singularity.
