[src:complex-analysis/residue-theorem] We may choose the path Ôüá $\gamma$ Ôüá to be a circle of radius Ôüá $\varepsilon$ Ôüá around Ôüá c Ôüá.
[src:complex-analysis/residue-theorem] Since Ôüá $\varepsilon$ Ôüá can be as small as we desire it can be made to contain only the singularity of Ôüá c Ôüá due to nature of isolated singularities.
[src:complex-analysis/residue-theorem] This may be used for calculation in cases where the integral can be calculated directly, but it is usually the case that residues are used to simplify calculation of integrals, and not the other way around.
[src:complex-analysis/residue-theorem] If the function Ôüá f Ôüá can be continued to a holomorphic function on the whole disk Ôüá $\vert y-c\vert <R$ Ôüá, then Ôüá $\operatorname {Res} (f,c)=0$ Ôüá.
[src:complex-analysis/residue-theorem] If that limit does not exist, then Ôüá f Ôüá instead has an essential singularity at Ôüá c Ôüá.
[src:complex-analysis/residue-theorem] If the limit is Ôüá 0 Ôüá, then Ôüá f Ôüá is either analytic at Ôüá c Ôüá or has a removable singularity there.
[src:complex-analysis/residue-theorem] If the limit is equal to infinity, then the order of the pole is higher than Ôüá 1 Ôüá.
[src:complex-analysis/residue-theorem] It may be that the function Ôüá f Ôüá can be expressed as a quotient of two functions, Ôüá $f(z)={g(z)}/{h(z)}$ Ôüá, where Ôüá g Ôüá and Ôüá h Ôüá are holomorphic functions in a neighbourhood of Ôüá c Ôüá, with Ôüá $h(c)=0$ Ôüá and Ôüá $h'(c)\neq 0$ Ôüá.
[src:complex-analysis/residue-theorem] This formula can be very useful in determining the residues for low-order poles.
[src:complex-analysis/residue-theorem] For higher-order poles, the calculations can become unmanageable, and series expansion is usually easier.
[src:complex-analysis/residue-theorem] For essential singularities, no such simple formula exists, and residues must usually be taken directly from series expansions.
[src:complex-analysis/residue-theorem] If parts or all of a function can be expanded into a Taylor series or Laurent series, which may be possible if the parts or the whole of the function has a standard series expansion, then calculating the residue is significantly simpler than by other methods.
[src:complex-analysis/residue-theorem] The residue of the function is simply given by the coefficient of Ôüá $(z-c)^{-1}$ Ôüá in the Laurent series expansion of the function.
